Here are some basic command lines that are commonly used by beginners:

pwd: Displays the present working directory (current directory).
ls: Lists the contents of the current directory.
-l: Displays the contents in a detailed format.
-a: Shows hidden files and directories.
cd: Changes the current directory.
cd [directory]: Moves to the specified directory.
cd ..: Moves to the parent directory.
mkdir: Creates a new directory.
mkdir [directory]: Creates a directory with the specified name.
touch: Creates a new file.
touch [filename]: Creates a file with the specified name.
rm: Removes files or directories.
rm [file]: Deletes the specified file.
rm -r [directory]: Deletes the specified directory and its contents recursively.
rm -f [file]: Forces the deletion of the specified file without prompting for confirmation.
cp: Copies files and directories.
cp [source] [destination]: Copies the source file/directory to the destination.
cp -r [source] [destination]: Copies the source directory and its contents recursively to the destination.
mv: Moves or renames files and directories.
mv [source] [destination]: Moves the source file/directory to the destination. Can also be used for renaming.
cat: Displays the contents of a file.
cat [filename]: Displays the contents of the specified file.
echo: Prints text or variables to the terminal.
echo [text]: Displays the specified text.
grep: Searches for a pattern in files.
grep [pattern] [file]: Searches for the specified pattern in the given file.
chmod: Changes the permissions of a file or directory.
chmod [permissions] [file/directory]: Modifies the permissions of the specified file or directory.
sudo: Executes a command with administrative privileges (superuser).
sudo [command]: Runs the specified command with superuser privileges.
man: Displays the manual pages for a command.
man [command]: Shows the manual pages for the specified command.
